      <data key="d1">COST_PROXY</data>
      <data key="d2">Estimated annual economic burden attributed to nosocomial infections in the United States.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LONG-TERM COST SAVINGS">
      <data key="d0">LONG-TERM COST SAVINGS</data>
      <data key="d1">COST_PROXY</data>
      <data key="d2">Projected economic benefit from scientifically grounded transmission analysis and optimized ventilation design (e.g., reduced infection-related costs).</data>
      <data key="d3">0.46</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SOURCE-TO-EXHAUST PATH (CONTAMINANT PATHWAY)">
      <data key="d0">SOURCE-TO-EXHAUST PATH (CONTAMINANT PATHWAY)</data>
      <data key="d1">EFFECTIVENESS_MEASURE</data>
      <data key="d2">Key hypothesized determinant of contaminant control: the airflow/transport pathway from contaminant source to exhaust; better control occurs when this path is direct and uninterrupted.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.61</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRFLOW PATH BETWEEN SOURCE AND EXHAUST (PATH PRINCIPLE)">
      <data key="d0">AIRFLOW PATH BETWEEN SOURCE AND EXHAUST (PATH PRINCIPLE)</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">Specific ventilation design concept stating that contaminant control improves when the transport path from contaminant source to exhaust is direct and uninterrupted (not broken by an air stream). Treated as the key mechanism underlying effective ventilation system design in the excerpt.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR CHANGE RATE (ACH)">
      <data key="d0">AIR CHANGE RATE (ACH)</data>
      <data key="d1">DOSE_OR_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation flow-rate metric (air changes per hour). The excerpt contrasts ACH with ventilation design, noting design may be more important overall, while higher ACH can make distance-related risk reduction more pronounced in transient coughing scenarios. | Air changes per hour in the bus cabin; increases with bus speed and with greater window opening, and is higher under exhaust-fan mode than supply-fan mode.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b,e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
      <data key="d6">AIR EXCHANGE RATE (ACH)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DISTANCE FROM CONTAMINANT SOURCE (DISTANCE FROM PATIENT)">
      <data key="d0">DISTANCE FROM CONTAMINANT SOURCE (DISTANCE FROM PATIENT)</data>
      <data key="d1">DOSE_OR_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">Proximity factor described as secondary: moving farther from the patient/contaminant source generally reduces infection risk in a transient coughing situation, with a stronger effect at higher ventilation flow rates.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.64</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
