      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONTAMINANTS">
      <data key="d0">CONTAMINANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Generic airborne contaminants/pathogens emitted from a source (implicitly the patient) whose transmission and control depend on the airflow path to exhaust; specific organisms are not identified in the excerpt.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFECTION RISK">
      <data key="d0">INFECTION RISK</data>
      <data key="d1">EFFECTIVENESS_MEASURE</data>
      <data key="d2">Effectiveness outcome discussed qualitatively: risk of infection transmission in a transient (coughing) scenario, reduced by increased distance from the patient and improved contaminant control via appropriate airflow-path design; effect can be more pronounced at higher ACH.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONTAMINANT TRANSMISSION AND CONTROL">
      <data key="d0">CONTAMINANT TRANSMISSION AND CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d1">EFFECTIVENESS_MEASURE</data>
      <data key="d2">Performance outcome describing how well contaminants are transported to exhaust and prevented from spreading; stated to be dominated by the source-to-exhaust path characteristics and influenced by distance and flow rate.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.66</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="THIS STUDY">
      <data key="d0">THIS STUDY</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">The study referenced in the excerpt providing evidence that (1) ventilation design consistent with the path principle can be more important than ACH for contaminant control and (2) increasing distance from the patient reduces infection risk in transient coughing, especially at higher flow rates.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">General building/HVAC ventilation (including different ventilation configurations) discussed as an engineering control affecting indoor airflow and contaminant dilution/transport in healthcare and other indoor environments. | An indoor air engineering control (e.g., outdoor air exchange and/or exhaust) intended to dilute and remove airborne contaminants. In the provided snippet it appears only as a MeSH term, with no operational parameters (e.g., ACH, flow rates, filtration, zones) or outcomes reported.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_4</data>
